definitions.definition: To move , either physically or in an abstract sense:

subdefinitions.definition: To move through space (especially to or through a place). ( May be used of tangible things such as people or cars, or intangible things such as moods or information. )
examples: Why don’t you go with us?
This train goes through Cincinnati on its way to Chicago.
Chris, where are you going ?
There's no public transit where I'm going .
Wow, look at him go !
The rumour went all around town.

subdefinitions.definition: To move or travel through time (either literally—in a fictional or hypothetical situation in which time travel is possible—or in one's mind or knowledge of the historical record). ( See also go back . )
examples: Yesterday was the second-wettest day on record; you have to go all the way back to 1896 to find a day when more rain fell.
Fans want to see the Twelfth Doctor go to the 51st century to visit River in the library.

subdefinitions.definition: To navigate (to a file or folder on a computer, a site on the internet, a memory, etc).
examples: For the best definitions, go to wiktionary.org

subdefinitions.definition: To move (a particular distance, or in a particular fashion).
examples: We've only gone twenty miles today.
This car can go circles around that one.
The fight went the distance and was decided on points.

subdefinitions.definition: To move or travel in order to do something, or to do something while moving.
examples: We went swimming.
Let's go shopping.
Please go and get me some envelopes.

subdefinitions.definition: To leave ; to move away.
examples: Please don't go !
I really must be going .
Workmen were coming and going at all hours of the night.

subdefinitions.definition: To follow or proceed according to (a course or path).
examples: Let's go this way for a while.
She was going that way anyway, so she offered to show him where it was.

subdefinitions.definition: To travel or pass along.
examples: We went the full length of the promenade before we found a place to sit down.
His life story goes the gamut, from poverty-stricken upbringing to colossal wealth.

subdefinitions.definition: To walk ; to travel on one's feet.

definitions.definition: To work or function (properly); to move or perform (as required).
examples: The engine just won't go anymore.
Don't put your hand inside while the motor's going !

definitions.definition: To start ; to begin (an action or process).
examples: You've got thirty seconds to solve the anagram, starting now. Go !

definitions.definition: To take a turn , especially in a game .
examples: It’s your turn; go .
I've got all vowels. I don't think I can go .

definitions.definition: To attend .
examples: I go to school at the schoolhouse.
She went to Yale.
They only go to church on Christmas.

definitions.definition: To proceed :

subdefinitions.definition: To proceed (often in a specified manner, indicating the perceived quality of an event or state).
examples: That went well.
"How are things going ?" "Not bad, thanks."

subdefinitions.definition: To proceed (especially to do something foolish ).
examples: Why'd you have to go and do that?
Why'd you have to go do that?
He just went and punched the guy.
subdefinitions.label_groups: intransitive , colloquial , with another verb, sometimes linked by and

definitions.definition: To extend along.
examples: The fence goes the length of the boundary.

definitions.definition: To extend (from one point in time or space to another).
examples: This property goes all the way to the state line.
The working week goes from Monday to Friday.

definitions.definition: To lead (to a place); to give access (to).
examples: Does this road go to Fort Smith?

definitions.definition: To become , move to or come to (a state, position, situation)

subdefinitions.definition: To become . ( The adjective that follows often, but not always, describes a negative state. )
examples: You'll go blind.
The milk went bad.
I went crazy.
After failing as a criminal, he decided to go straight.
The video clip went viral.
Don't tell my Mum: she'll go ballistic.
The local shop wants to go digital, and eventually go global.

subdefinitions.definition: To move to (a position or state).
examples: If we can win on Saturday, we'll go top of the league.
They went level with their rivals.

subdefinitions.definition: To come (to a certain condition or state).
examples: They went into debt .
She goes to sleep around 10 o'clock.

definitions.definition: To change (from one value to another).
examples: The traffic light went straight from green to red.

definitions.definition: To assume the obligation or function of; to be, to serve as.
To continuously or habitually be in a state.
examples: I don't want my children to go hungry.
We went barefoot in the summer.

definitions.definition: To turn out , to result ; to come to (a certain result).
examples: The decision went the way we expected.

definitions.definition: To tend (toward a result)
examples: Well, that goes to show you.
These experiences go to make us stronger.

definitions.definition: To contribute to a (specified) end product or result.
examples: qualities that go to make a lady / lip-reader / sharpshooter

definitions.definition: To pass , to be used up:

subdefinitions.definition: To elapse , to pass ; to slip away. ( Compare go by . )
examples: The time went slowly.

subdefinitions.definition: To end or disappear . ( Compare go away . )
examples: After three days, my headache finally went .

subdefinitions.definition: To be spent or used up .
examples: His money went on drink.

definitions.definition: To die .
examples: I want to go in my sleep.

definitions.definition: To be lost or out :

subdefinitions.definition: To be lost .
examples: The third wicket went just before lunch.

subdefinitions.definition: To be out .
examples: Smith bowls ... Jones hits it straight up in the air ... and ... caught! Jones has gone !

definitions.definition: To break down or apart:

subdefinitions.definition: To collapse or give way, to break apart.
examples: Careful! It looks as if that ceiling could go at any moment!

subdefinitions.definition: To break down or decay .
examples: My mind is going .
She's 83; her eyesight is starting to go .

definitions.definition: To be sold .
examples: The car went for five thousand dollars.
The store is closing down so everything must go .

definitions.definition: To be discarded or disposed of.
examples: This chair has got to go .
All this old rubbish can go .

definitions.definition: To be given , especially to be assigned or allotted .
examples: The property shall go to my wife.
The award went to Steven Spielberg.

definitions.definition: To survive or get by ; to last or persist for a stated length of time.
examples: How long can you go without water?
We've gone without your help for a while now.
I've gone ten days now without a cigarette.
Can you two go twenty minutes without arguing?!

definitions.definition: To have a certain record .
examples: They've gone one for three in this series.
The team is going five in a row.

definitions.definition: To be authoritative, accepted, or valid:

subdefinitions.definition: Of an opinion or instruction, to have (final) authority ; to be authoritative.
examples: Whatever the boss says goes , do you understand?

subdefinitions.definition: To be accepted .
examples: Anything goes around here.

subdefinitions.definition: To be valid or applicable .
examples: The baked beans can go on this shelf, and the same goes for all these other tins.

definitions.definition: To say (something), to make a sound:

subdefinitions.definition: To say (something, aloud or to oneself).
examples: I go , "As if!" And she was all like, "Whatever!"
As soon as I did it, I went "that was stupid."

subdefinitions.definition: To make the (specified) sound.
examples: Cats go "meow". Motorcycles go "vroom".

subdefinitions.definition: To sound ; to make a noise.
examples: I woke up just before the clock went .

definitions.definition: To be expressed or composed (a certain way).
examples: The tune goes like this.
As the story goes , he got the idea for the song while sitting in traffic.

definitions.definition: To resort (to).
examples: The nylon gears kept breaking, so we went to stainless steel.

definitions.definition: To apply or subject oneself to:

subdefinitions.definition: To apply oneself; to undertake; to have as one's goal or intention. ( Compare be going to . )
examples: I'm going to join a sports team.
I wish you'd go and get a job.
He went to pick it up, but it rolled out of reach.
He's going to leave town tomorrow.

subdefinitions.definition: To make an effort , to subject oneself (to something).
examples: You didn't have to go to such trouble.
I never thought he'd go so far as to call you.
She went to great expense to help them win.

subdefinitions.definition: To work (through or over), especially mentally .
examples: I've gone over this a hundred times.
Let's not go into that right now.

definitions.definition: To fit (in a place, or together with something):

subdefinitions.definition: To fit .
examples: Do you think the sofa will go through the door?
The belt just barely went around his waist.
subdefinitions.label_groups: intransitive , often followed by a preposition

subdefinitions.definition: To be compatible , especially of colors or food and drink.
examples: This shade of red doesn't go with the drapes.
White wine goes better with fish than red wine.

subdefinitions.definition: To belong (somewhere).
examples: My shirts go on this side of the wardrobe.
This piece of the jigsaw goes on the other side.

subdefinitions.definition: Of a ball, to be capable of being potted, not having its path to the pocket obstructed by other balls.
examples: He'd like to pot the pink, but I don't think it will go . The green's in the way.

definitions.definition: To date .
examples: How long have they been going together?
He's been going with her for two weeks.

definitions.definition: To (begin to) date or have sex with (a particular race).
To attack :

subdefinitions.definition: To fight or attack .
examples: I went at him with a knife.

subdefinitions.definition: To fight .
To attack .

definitions.definition: Used to express how some category of things generally is, as a reference for, contrast to, or comparison with, a particular example.
examples: My cat Fluffy is very timid, as cats go .
As far as burgers go , this is one of the best.

definitions.definition: To take (a particular part or share ); to participate in to the extent of.
examples: Let's go halves on this.

definitions.definition: To yield or weigh .
examples: Those babies go five tons apiece.

definitions.definition: To offer , bid or bet an amount; to pay .
examples: That's as high as I can go .
We could go two fifty.
I'll go a ten-spot.
I'll go you a shilling.
I'll go him one better .

definitions.definition: To enjoy . ( Compare go for . )
examples: I could go a beer right about now.

definitions.definition: To go to the toilet ; to urinate or defecate .
examples: I really need to go .
Have you managed to go today, Mrs. Miggins?

definitions.definition: Expressing encouragement or approval.
examples: Go , girl! You can do it!

definitions.definition: Clipping of go to the .
definitions.label_groups: UK , especially MLE , Australia , Singapore , intransitive , colloquial

definitions.definition: To fight , usually with the fists.
examples: You said WHAT about my mom? Do you want to go , bro?

definitions.definition: To pass (a specified time) in gestation ; to be pregnant .
